<DOC><DOCNO> AP890921-0255 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1303EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Monsanto-Mobil     09-21 0179</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Monsanto-Mobil,0189</SECOND><HEAD>Mobil Ordered To Pay $21 Million in Contract Suit</HEAD><DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal jury has awarded Monsanto Co. morethan $21 million for an alleged breach of contract by Mobil OilCorp. to buy pure phosphorus produced at plants in Idaho andTennessee.   Monsanto contended Mobil violated a five-year agreement to buythe phosphorus and other products, including detergents andlubrication additives, at Mobil plants in suburban Cincinnati andCharleston, S.C.   A six-member jury in U.S. District Court deliberated two hoursWednesday before awarding $21,126,557 to Monsanto.   Mobil contended during the trial, which began Sept. 11, that itssale of the Ohio and South Carolina plants to Albright andamp; Wilson Inc.in April 1985 negated the contract with Monsanto.   ``We obviously disagree with the verdict. It's a complexcommercial case,'' said Richard A. Ahrens, a lawyer for Mobil. Hesaid Mobil would ask the judge to overturn the verdict or order anew trial.   Monsanto produced elemental phosphorus _ the pure, uncombinedchemical element _ at plants in Soda Springs, Idaho, and Columbia,Tenn.</TEXT></DOC>